STew spatial transcriptomic data count modeling tutorial on DLFCP data

We benchmarked five different statistical models (negative binomial, zero-inflated negative binomial, GLM Poisson, zero-inflated Poisson, and Hurdle) with the potential to model overdispersed count data, aiming to pinpoint the right model for identifying significant genes associated with the discerned spatial informed axes (sCVs, Sparse Canonical Vectors) or identified clusters. In this framework, we allow users to incorporate covariates, such as log(nUMI). Because we may want to account for the potential confounding effects such as sequencing depth and sample size in our modeling.By controlling for the covariates, we can ensure that the observed associations between gene expression and a specific sCV are not solely driven by variations in sequencing depth.

Further, we use Rootogram analysis and other statistics like AIC to assess the goodness of model fit at the count level for each gene.

Here, we present a tutorial of this work using the DLPFC (human dorsolateral prefrontal cortex) spatial transcriptomic data.

N = 500
spatial <- dlpfc$spatial

count_exp <- dlpfc$count_exp %>% t() %>% as.data.frame()

# Convert row names to a column in count_exp
count_exp <- count_exp %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column('cell')

# Compute variance for each gene
gene_variances <- apply(count_exp[ , sapply(count_exp, is.numeric)], 2, var, na.rm = TRUE)

# Rank genes by variance
ranked_genes <- sort(gene_variances, decreasing = TRUE)

# Select the top N genes
top_genes <- names(ranked_genes)[1:N]  # replace N with the number of top genes you want

# Convert row names to a column in spatial
spatial <- spatial %>%
  tibble::rownames_to_column('cell')

count_exp$nUMI <- rowSums(count_exp[sapply(count_exp, is.numeric)], na.rm=TRUE)


dt <- count_exp %>%
  dplyr::left_join(spatial, by = 'cell')
#dt = dt[,top_genes]

dt <- dt %>%
  dplyr::select(c( imagecol,imagerow,top_genes, 'nUMI'))

results = multimodel_count_regression(outcomes_interest= top_genes,  # a vector of genes of interest
                                  models=   c("GLM", "ZeroInflated", "ZeroInflNegBinomial", "NegativeBinomial", "Hurdle")
,          # a vector of models to use (e.g., "GLM", "ZeroInflated", etc.)
                                  plot_density= F,    # a logical value, if TRUE, plots density
                                  plot_qq= F,         # a logical value, if TRUE, plots Q-Q plot
                                  estimate = F,        # a logical value, if TRUE, calculates estimates
                                  avg_effect  = T,        # a logical value, if TRUE, log-transforms the plots
                                  rootogram = F,       # a logical value, if TRUE, creates rootogram
                                  full_model = '~ CC1 + log(nUMI)' ,      # a formula describing the full model to be tested
                                  null_model = '~ log(nUMI)',      # a formula describing the null model to be compared with the full model
                                  data  = dt,      #  data set to use for the analysis, MUST BE COUNT DATA NOT LOG NORMALIZED
                                  workers = 4,

Volcano plot

To visualy determine the genes that are associated with the CCs, we are only going to grab those that are of in range (inf,-0.1) , (0.1, inf).

threshold_pval <- -log(0.05)
threshold_est = 1
  
estimates %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = Estimate, y = -log(lrt_pval), color = ifelse((-log(lrt_pval) > threshold_pval) & (abs(Estimate) > threshold_est), "above", "below"))) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("above" = "red", "below" = "black")) +
  theme_classic() +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = threshold_est), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = -threshold_est), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = threshold_pval), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  facet_wrap(~model)+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Rootogram: how to diagnose and interpret model fitting at count level

Rootograms are a good tool to determine the performance of a model by showing difference in counts between observed and predicted by models that specialize in count data or poisson distribution. Essentially its an upside down histogram of observed values where instead of starting in the x axis, it starts from the predicted models predictions. Below there is an example with the gene ENSG00000188536 found in the DLFCP data. We would like to determine the values where the model over or under estimates the count at a specific value. In the red circle we can see that the model is over estimating that count by the square root of the frequency. In the other hand, the blue circle shows the over estimation of our model by also the squared root of the frequency.

gene = "ENSG00000188536"

mod = glm( ENSG00000188536 ~ CC1, data = dt, family = 'poisson')
rootogram(mod)
